faq:
  - q: "How do I calculate how much gravel I need?"
    a: "Measure the length and width of the area, choose a depth, and calculate volume. This calculator converts that volume into cubic feet, cubic yards, estimated weight, tons, bags, and cost."
  - q: "How deep should gravel be for landscaping?"
    a: "Decorative gravel areas are often around 2 inches deep. Walkways, drainage areas, and base layers may need more depth depending on the project and site conditions."
  - q: "How many cubic feet are in a cubic yard of gravel?"
    a: "There are 27 cubic feet in one cubic yard. Gravel suppliers often sell bulk gravel by the cubic yard or by the ton."
  - q: "How many tons of gravel do I need?"
    a: "Tons depend on volume and material density. This calculator estimates tons by multiplying cubic feet by the selected pounds-per-cubic-foot density, then dividing by 2,000."
  - q: "What gravel density should I use?"
    a: "If your supplier provides a density, use that number. For rough planning, loose landscape gravel is often estimated around 95 to 105 pounds per cubic foot, but materials vary."
  - q: "Is pea gravel lighter than crushed stone?"
    a: "It can be, depending on stone type, size, moisture, and compaction. Crushed stone, river rock, pea gravel, and base gravel can all have different weights."
  - q: "Should I add overage when ordering gravel?"
    a: "Yes. A 5–10% overage helps account for uneven ground, settling, compaction, spillage, and measuring differences."
  - q: "Should I use landscape fabric under gravel?"
    a: "Landscape fabric can help reduce weeds and keep gravel from mixing into soil, but drainage, slope, and project type matter."
  - q: "How much does a 50 lb bag of gravel cover?"
    a: "Coverage depends on depth. A 50 lb bag covers much more area at 1 inch deep than at 3 inches deep. Use the bag weight and density settings to estimate bag count."
  - q: "Is bulk gravel cheaper than bagged gravel?"
    a: "Bulk gravel is often more cost-effective for larger projects. Bagged gravel may be easier for small projects, limited storage, or areas without delivery access."
